WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:03.340
Hi, pleasure to be here.

00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:11.590
So yeah, this talk is going to be about

00:00:11.770 --> 00:00:13.970
the design philosophy behind BookHive.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.600
So it's not actually like design in terms of like UI

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:20.260
design, although I did do a redesign last week, released

00:00:20.260 --> 00:00:21.510
it, all that.

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:24.600
So you can enjoy the website now.

00:00:24.610 --> 00:00:29.800
But this is going to be more about the philosophical aspects of

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:30.520
this.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:34.680
So I think that what we have here with AT protocol is

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:37.480
really a trend reversal.

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:44.690
We have a trend reversal in terms of the web started as

00:00:44.710 --> 00:00:50.090
being open and then we slowly saw this being clawed back

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:54.340
by these systems, these large social networks.

00:00:54.660 --> 00:00:59.580
There was things like Twitter used to have an open API,

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:01.560
Reddit used to have an open API.

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:04.360
They slowly crawled that back from us.

00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:07.990
And I think that what we have with AT protocol is we

00:01:07.990 --> 00:01:14.540
're right now running into user agency at an all time low

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:15.060
.

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:20.770
So what this means is that like we're constantly being forced

00:01:20.770 --> 00:01:23.080
to do these Windows updates.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:26.640
We've all been sunsetted by by some sort of

00:01:27.370 --> 00:01:32.660
application and just essentially screwed over.

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:32.720
And we have no other recourse.

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:37.500
These APIs are closing down and we increasingly, with AI now

00:01:37.510 --> 00:01:39.140
, data is seen as a moat.

00:01:39.140 --> 00:01:42.980
So there's only more incentive and pressure to close down these

00:01:43.070 --> 00:01:43.720
APIs.

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:49.140
Whereas AT protocol, as we all know, is meant to

00:01:49.390 --> 00:01:50.280
be open.

00:01:50.290 --> 00:01:54.480
So when the web first came out, there was this idea

00:01:54.490 --> 00:01:57.920
of a user agent that I think that we just kind of

00:01:57.920 --> 00:01:58.940
forgot about.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:03.160
Like, it used to be that the idea of a user

00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:07.560
agent was meant to be that when you're looking at a

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:10.560
document or something, you might have some preferences.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:11.560
We're all different people.

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:13.530
We all have different preferences.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:16.560
Why are we all looking at the exact same interface?

00:02:16.570 --> 00:02:20.190
It doesn't make sense.

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:23.800
You know, something as simple as the font size or your

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:24.200
font family.

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:30.870
So the idea of this user agent largely just didn't pan

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:36.510
out, but we're all trying to do something better.

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:39.100
And I think that's what AT protocol is all about.

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:44.820
So my little slice of this is working on something called Book

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:45.840
Hive.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:47.840
It's an alternative to Goodreads.

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:52.540
So you can track your books, organize shelves, and all

00:02:52.630 --> 00:02:58.480
of that data is stored in the user's PDFs.

00:02:58.490 --> 00:03:03.520
So when I was designing what to store for BookHive

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:06.240
, when you could imagine this sort of system, all that

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:11.680
it really needs is some identifier for a book, whether the

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:14.320
person has actually read the book or not, when did they

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:14.830
do it.

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:17.120
That's all that you really need to store to the user

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:17.480
system.

00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:20.870
So you could literally just store this, and that would be

00:03:20.890 --> 00:03:23.100
enough to render the BookHive UI.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:27.100
But what does this give the user?

00:03:27.130 --> 00:03:29.070
It's just some random identifier.

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:30.680
It's absolutely useless to them.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:32.710
They can't do anything with this data.

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:36.320
So this is what I actually store.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:39.120
I give the people their book.

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:42.000
They want to know the book's title, the author,

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:44.010
the actual cover art.

00:03:44.170 --> 00:03:47.120
I actually upload it to your PDF as a blog.

00:03:47.130 --> 00:03:48.680
And all these other data.

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:53.060
There's also, particularly with books, there's no real

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:55.760
standard identifier for a book.

00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:57.860
It's an open problem.

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:01.730
Everybody, every dataset has this different identifier for a book.

00:04:03.370 --> 00:04:06.260
So I give you everything that I know about the book,

00:04:06.260 --> 00:04:08.600
anything that I have, I try to give it to the

00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:09.320
user.

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:14.190
It's all about giving the user what's maximally useful

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:14.950
to them.

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:20.250
So we have an opportunity to build social software where data actually

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:22.000
belongs to people.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.880
Let's not waste it by giving people just these random ident

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:28.640
ifiers that they can't do anything with.

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:33.280
The PDF is not just a database.

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:37.690
So you normally think of a database as trying to store like

00:04:37.690 --> 00:04:40.230
the minimal representation.

00:04:40.410 --> 00:04:43.250
It's not about efficiency.

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:44.890
It's about agency.

00:04:44.930 --> 00:04:49.160
So there's a little bit of a thought experiment that you

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:51.920
can take with this sort of thing.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:56.220
If BookHive went down, which it does all the

00:04:56.220 --> 00:04:57.520
time, it runs in my living room.

00:04:57.570 --> 00:05:02.200
Is the data on your PDS actually useful to you?

00:05:02.350 --> 00:05:06.570
And I'll get back to that as well, because I

00:05:06.570 --> 00:05:10.160
forgot to reorder these slides.

00:05:10.210 --> 00:05:15.020
So one way that I handle this is with a central data

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:16.030
store.

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:18.680
So what this means that's on protocol.

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:21.790
So normally centralization is a bad thing.

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:24.840
But in this case, what I'm doing is I,

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:27.800
I did, as I said before, and I give each

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:31.960
user their data in their PDS, but I also have

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:35.720
this one little URI that it uploads.

00:05:35.730 --> 00:05:39.210
It makes a link to the BookHive Buzz account as

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:41.340
like a service account.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:48.160
And this makes a central point of knowing all of the data

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:52.080
, not everything that you need to, to, to store

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:54.030
into the user's PDS.

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:56.920
They might not care about a book description, or I can

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:59.280
't make an update to a book if there's ever some

00:05:59.280 --> 00:06:01.080
, some sort of a amendment.

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:05.420
But we can, everybody can reference this and we can all

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:09.080
talk about the same book using these URIs.

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:12.330
And there's an interesting opportunity here for, for doing things

00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:13.320
like backlinks.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:16.320
Honestly, I haven't really explored this that much.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:19.080
It's only been out for a week now.

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:25.040
So here's some proof that this user agency and that the

00:06:25.110 --> 00:06:28.080
data is actually useful.

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:29.990
PopFeed.

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:33.320
PopFeed actually is able to interoperate with Book

00:06:33.470 --> 00:06:34.050
Hive.

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:37.210
They're able to display all of the book data because they

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:38.080
have all of the book data.

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:44.610
Another example is Book Explorer, which was made by Tice

00:06:44.610 --> 00:06:45.080
.

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:49.380
Tice actually, he wanted to be able to manage his

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:52.970
books in a different application.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:58.580
So he, he made this table view and you can completely

00:06:58.830 --> 00:07:00.080
use a different front end.

00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:02.080
It doesn't have to be BookHive.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:02.080
This is real interop.

00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:09.370
The only reason that all of this works is about is because

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:15.120
BookHive stores the maximally useful data in service of

00:07:15.120 --> 00:07:16.070
the user.

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:23.490
So there's some takeaways here for builders since everybody here is

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:27.080
related on the building side.

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:30.460
Store what's useful to the user, not just what's

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:32.080
useful to you.

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:35.200
You may only need those identifiers, but give the people

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:36.080
their data.

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:37.080
It's theirs.

00:07:37.090 --> 00:07:44.080
Wherever possible, try to use standard identifiers.

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:49.970
And I'm actually out of data, out of time.

00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:51.790
All right.

00:07:52.350 --> 00:07:53.080
All right.

00:07:53.090 --> 00:07:57.840
Empower users, be their agents, open data, open

00:07:57.870 --> 00:07:59.040
source.

00:07:59.110 --> 00:08:00.080
Thank you very much.

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:06.040
Thank you so much, Nick.

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:09.700
Unfortunately, we do not have time for another for any questions

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:12.080
, but oh, sorry.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:14.070
Yes, actually, we have time for one question.

00:08:14.090 --> 00:08:14.760
You're right.

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:15.030
Yes.

00:08:15.070 --> 00:08:16.080
In total is 10 minutes.

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.080
Does anybody have a question?

00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:20.040
Yes.

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:21.080
Let me bring this to you.

00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:25.130
I don't know if it's much of a question,

00:08:25.130 --> 00:08:30.080
but my comment, and I said this to you before,

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:32.670
I like that this is a good low hanging fruit for people

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:35.070
to migrate from Goodreads away.

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:37.620
That's what I tell my friends is like, this is

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:41.050
one of these apps that you can already use, whereas with

00:08:41.050 --> 00:08:42.080
social media, it's a little more difficult.

00:08:42.090 --> 00:08:44.330
People like, oh, private groups and stuff is like,

00:08:44.370 --> 00:08:46.240
well, it's not working with AppRoto, but

00:08:46.240 --> 00:08:49.140
for Goodreads, I think as an alternative, it

00:08:49.210 --> 00:08:50.080
's really great.

00:08:50.090 --> 00:08:54.420
With the data structures that you have, like as the whole

00:08:54.440 --> 00:08:57.140
on your PDS, like, I guess we could just

00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:58.080
clone it down.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:08:59.080
Right.

00:08:59.090 --> 00:09:02.730
Do you offer, like, the database itself, too,

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:04.080
for download?

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:07.080
Amazing.

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:11.940
Thank you.

